Getting Started with GraphQL

4 steps
Completed

The first tutorial in this GraphQL module will introduce you to the basic GraphQL concepts and benefits. This tutorial will also feature a refresher on REST API where you will make a GET request using Postman.

Next Tutorial
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Make a GET request on Postman
  • Explain GraphQL in simple terms
  • State the differences between REST API and GraphQL
  • List the benefits of GraphQL

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Refresher on REST APIs

    Before we begin working with GraphQL, we will revisit what REST APIs are to better understand the difference between REST APIs and GraphQL. Watch the What is REST API? Examples And How To Use It video on a quick overview of what REST APIs and how REST APIs are called.

    POST, GET, PUT, and DELETE are the four main REST API methods. A POST request creates a new resource and requires a body of data to be parsed in order to do so. To retrieve data, a GET request is used. PUT requests are used to change or update the state of a resource. DELETE requests are used to remove a resource from the system.

    Let us use a simple restaurant analogy for context. You place an order with the restaurant with a POST request, and your order is sent to the kitchen. You check with the waiter to ensure that your order has been submitted with a GET request. When you make a PUT request, you update your order request, and your updated order is sent to the kitchen for preparation. A DELETE request is made to the kitchen to cancel your order and your order will no longer be prepared.

  • Step 2: REST API with Postman

    Postman is a free and open source API testing platform. It is a HTTP client that provides a ready-to-use environment for testing REST API endpoints with a user interface and we will make a simple GET request using the Postman web app. JSONPlaceholder offers free mock APIs for testing and prototyping, and we will make a GET request to the posts endpoint. 

    Head over to Postman to register for an account if you do not already have one. Once you have signed up for a free Postman account, proceed to login and launch the Postman web application.

    You should see the Postman home page as shown and click on “Create New” to make your REST API request.

    Click on “HTTP Request” and you should see the Postman interface. Next, head over to JSONPlaceholder and navigate to the resources section where you will observe that there are 6 out of the box resources available for query. Further, notice that there is a value associated with each endpoint, this represents the number of datapoints available per endpoint. We will only be using the posts endpoint for this tutorial.

    Navigate back to Postman and under the URL section, replace the “Enter request URL” field with the following URL -  https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts and ensure that the request type is a GET request.

    Click on the “Send” button and your GET request will be sent to the JSONPlaceholder server. Under the response section, you should see that the posts object has been sent from the server as a JSON object with a status code of 200 indicating a successful GET request.

    Your Postman response should look like this:

  • Step 3: GraphQL vs REST API

    Now that you understand how REST APIs work, you should notice that the general design of REST APIs is to make everything an endpoint. GraphQL, on the other hand, enables developers to create a single endpoint with a clear description of the data available via type specification. This gives the developer the ability to request only the data that they require as GraphQL is a strongly typed language.

    Let's make a comparison between REST API and GraphQL. Consider that we have to fetch both posts and albums from the JSONPlaceholder endpoints. With REST APIs, you would have to make 2 requests to first the posts endpoints and the albums endpoints in order to fetch all the data required.

    With GraphQL, you can define a new query instead that wraps both endpoints, and the server will combine and filter the backend data to return exactly what is requested

    A mock query on GraphQL to return posts and album will take the form of:

    query getPostsAndAlbums {
 posts {
 userId,
 title,
 body,
 }
albums {
 userId,
 title,
 }
}
    GraphQL

    When you run this query, you'll get a JSON response with information on both the posts and albums with the above fields. Hence, we can see the benefits of GraphQL, where developers can avoid making multiple requests to fetch data from different endpoints. Most importantly, GraphQL gives developers the ability to define their desired response output!

  • Step 4: Testing Your Knowledge

    You’ve learnt quite a bit about GraphQL and the difference between REST API and GraphQL! Time to put your knowledge to the test.
